-! # how to errors: 007-lit-bytes-unterminated.zo
-!
-! @cmd: `zo build 007-lit-bytes-unterminated.zo`
-!
-! Sometimes, Unicode is too much. When you are talking to a network 
-! or reading a file, you just want the raw "Byte"—a number from 0 to 255. 
-!
-! In zo, we write a byte using backticks: `` `z` ``. 
-!
-! Just like strings and characters, a byte must be enclosed. If you leave a
-! backtick hanging, the compiler will go looking for its partner until the end
-! of the line.

fun main() {
  -- Mistake: The byte literal is never closed.
  imu b: bytes = `z;
}

-! ## the diagnostic map.
-!
-! zo identifies the opening backtick `` ` `` and expects exactly one 
-! character and a closing backtick. When it doesn't find it, it 
-! alerts you that the "Raw Byte" is incomplete.
-!
-! ## try this.
-!
-!   1. Add the closing backtick: `` `z` ``.
-!   2. Compare a byte to a char: what is the difference between `` `z` `` and
-!      `'z'`? (Hint: One is 8-bit, the other is 32-bit!).
-!
-! Note: Byte literals are currently being refined in the compiler. They are 
-!       "parsed" but not yet fully ready for runtime work.

-- EXPECTED OUTPUT:
-- [E0518] Error: Unterminated bytes literal
--     ╭─[ 007-lit-bytes-unterminated.zo:16:18 ]
--     │
--  16 │   imu b: bytes = `z;
--     │                  ─┬─
--     │                   ╰─── unterminated byte literal
--     │
--     │ Help: Close the literal by adding a backtick at the end
--     │
--     │ Note: A byte literal represents a single 8-bit value.
--     │       It must start and end with a backtick
-- ────╯
